Spring Boot -- when and why
==========================

1. Spring Boot follows a monolithic classloader -- the entire application shares one classpath. When you update a library, you redeploy everything. This is perfectly fine for 95% of applications, especially when paired with CI/CD and rolling deployments.

Spring Boot is the default choice for most backend applications. You pick it when you want fast development velocity with convention-over-configuration, a mature ecosystem (Spring Data, Security, Cloud), embedded server deployment as a single JAR, and straightforward microservices architecture. 

OSGi
====
1.OSGi is a modular runtime where each bundle (JAR) has its own classloader and explicitly declares what it exports and imports. You'd consider it in a narrow set of scenarios.
2.It is used for Long-running platform applications where you need hot-deploy of individual modules without restarting the JVM 
3.Plugin-based architectures where third parties write extensions that get loaded at runtime  like an enterprise integration platform where customers drop in custom adapters without rebuilding the host application. 
4. it is useful when you need strict module isolation.
5. It helps as a third party when a service needs it, extends with plugins at runtime

when not use OSGi
-----------------
1. OSGi adds complexity in bundle lifecycle management, service registry wiring, dependency resolution at runtime, and debugging classloader issues. 
